<p class="drop-cap">Sixteen steps. From that first glimpse through heavy wooden doors, through Trinitarian theology and icons, through sacraments and saints and the long painful history of division. Maybe you started out of idle curiosity. Maybe something drew you forward that you cannot quite name. Whatever brought you here, the question is simple now.</p>

<p>What next?</p>

<p>This is not a sales pitch. Eastern Christianity does not do sales pitches. It has a Liturgy, an open door, and an ancient conviction that beauty and truth, encountered honestly, do their own work.</p>

<h2>For the Curious</h2>

<p>Just come.</p>

<p>Attend a <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#divine-liturgy">Divine Liturgy</a>. No call ahead. No appointment. No prerequisites. The service will be longer than you expect, probably 60 to 90 minutes. Almost everything is sung. There will be incense. The priest will face the altar for much of it, not the congregation. People will cross themselves and bow and prostrate at moments you cannot predict.</p>

<p>This is fine. No one expects you to know the choreography. Stand when others stand. Sit when others sit. Let it wash over you.</p>

<p>You will not be asked to fill out a visitor card. You will not be cornered by a greeter with a name tag. But if it is a healthy parish, someone will invite you to coffee hour afterward and hand you a plate of food before you have finished introducing yourself. Accept the food. Ask the questions.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— The emissaries of Prince Vladimir of Kyiv, upon attending the Divine Liturgy at Hagia Sophia, 987 AD">
  We knew not whether we were in heaven or on earth, for on earth there is no such splendor or beauty. We only know that God dwells there among men.
</Pullquote>

<h2>For the Serious Inquirer</h2>

<p>If curiosity has grown into something that will not let go, talk to the priest. Eastern priests are generally accessible. They are accustomed to inquirers. Tell them where you are: what drew you, what questions remain, what holds you back.</p>

<p>Most Byzantine Catholic parishes have a catechetical process for those preparing to enter the Church. Not a class you pass or fail. A period of learning, prayer, and discernment, typically several months to a year. You learn the faith, the sacraments, the liturgical year, the spiritual life. You begin attending Liturgy regularly, fasting, developing a prayer rule.</p>

<p>The culmination is reception through the sacraments of initiation: Baptism (if unbaptized), <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#chrismation">Chrismation</a>, and the Eucharist, all together. If you have been baptized in another Christian tradition, your baptism is typically recognized. You are received through Chrismation and Communion. Kallistos Ware's <em>The Orthodox Way</em> is an excellent companion for this period of discernment.</p>

