<h2>For Latin Catholics</h2>

<p>You have a standing invitation.</p>

<p>Attend any Byzantine Catholic parish. Participate fully. Receive the Eucharist. No permission needed. The Byzantine Catholic churches are in full communion with Rome. What is celebrated at that altar is the same Body and Blood you receive at your Latin parish, offered in a different rite within the same Catholic communion.</p>

<p>Many Latin Catholics discover in the Byzantine tradition something they had been missing without knowing it. A deeper sense of mystery. A richer theology of the spiritual life. Elements of early Christianity that the West has attenuated. You can attend both. Some eventually transfer their canonical enrollment to a Byzantine Catholic church, a process requiring both bishops' permission but neither unusual nor difficult.</p>

<p>You lose nothing by exploring. You gain a second lung.</p>

<h2>For Orthodox Christians</h2>

<p>This is the most delicate section in the entire journey. The relationship between Byzantine Catholics and Orthodox is complex, painful, and full of history. No pretending otherwise.</p>

<p>Byzantine Catholics and Orthodox share virtually everything: the same Liturgy, the same theology, the same spirituality, the same Fathers, the same icons. The difference is ecclesiological. The question of communion with Rome. For some Orthodox, Byzantine Catholics represent an unacceptable compromise. For Byzantine Catholics, the opposite: a bridge, a witness that Eastern and Western Christianity can coexist in communion.</p>

<p>If you are Orthodox and feel drawn toward communion with Rome, the door is open. A Byzantine Catholic parish will feel like home. The transition involves no repudiation of your Orthodox faith or practice. Same Liturgy. Same icons. Same spiritual traditions. What changes is canonical reality.</p>

<p>No proselytizing. No claims of monopoly. Simply existence, and the rest left to the Holy Spirit.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— Metropolitan Andrey Sheptytsky">
  Love your own rite, your own Church, your own tradition — but never at the expense of love for your brothers and sisters in Christ, wherever they may worship.
</Pullquote>

<h2>For Those New to Christianity</h2>

<p>Perhaps you arrived here with no Christian background at all. The Byzantine tradition just happened to be the form in which you first encountered it.</p>

<p>Welcome.</p>

<p>The Eastern Church does not ask you to check your intellect at the door or accept propositions on blind faith. It asks you to enter an experience: worship, beauty, prayer, community. To see whether, within that experience, you encounter the living God. The theology comes later, as reflection on the encounter. The encounter comes first.</p>

<p>Talk to a priest. Attend Liturgy. Read the Gospels. Pray, even if uncertain anyone is listening. The Eastern tradition has great patience with seekers. Some saints took decades to find their way. There is no deadline.</p>

