<h2>Finding a Parish</h2>

<p><strong>United States:</strong> The Byzantine Catholic Metropolitan Church of Pittsburgh maintains a parish directory. The Ruthenian, Ukrainian, Melkite, and other Eastern Catholic eparchies each have locators on their websites.</p>

<p><strong>Canada:</strong> The Ukrainian Catholic Eparchy of Edmonton, the Eparchy of Toronto, and the Slovak Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius all maintain directories.</p>

<p><strong>Worldwide:</strong> The Catholic Near East Welfare Association (CNEWA) provides information on Eastern Catholic communities globally.</p>

<p>If no Byzantine Catholic parish exists near you, an Orthodox parish will offer a virtually identical liturgical experience, though intercommunion is not possible. Any Latin Catholic parish will welcome you into the same communion, even if the rite differs.</p>

<h2>Not a Conclusion</h2>

<p>A website can only do so much. The real journey begins when you walk through actual doors into an actual church, where actual people are singing actual hymns to a God they believe is actually present.</p>

<p>The <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#theotokos">Theotokos</a> waits in the apse. The saints watch from the walls. The incense rises. The priest chants: <em>"Blessed is the Kingdom of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit, now and ever and unto ages of ages."</em></p>

<p><strong>"Amen."</strong></p>

<p>Come and see.</p>

